  "beats": [
    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "This is Liam, in for Bear. One operator raises an angular-momentum projection by exactly h-bar; another lowers it. But the ladder cannot continue forever. Its forced endpoints quantize the entire spectrum.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "remotion",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "provenance": "proven-core/ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "command": "Why must the angular-momentum ladder terminate at a top and bottom rung?",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS — ANGULAR MOMENTUM",
            "segment": "Why Angular Momentum Comes in a Ladder",
            "greeting": "Namaste, Liam",
            "runningText": "checking ladder-state norms for nonnegativity…",
            "output": [
              "L-plus and L-minus shift m by one.",
              "Endpoint norms force m from -j to +j."
            ],
            "folderLabel": "@NikBearBrown",
            "modelLabel": "Fable 5",
            "effortLabel": "High"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B01.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.69,
      "build": {
        "status": "VIDEO",
        "src": "media/B01.mp4",
        "filled_by": "media",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "act": "SETUP",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Choose simultaneous eigenstates of total angular momentum squared and its z projection. Label them j comma m. Total magnitude stays fixed by j, while m records the projection in units of h-bar.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.99,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "RAISE",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Apply L-plus. If the result is nonzero, it has the same j and projection m plus one. Apply L-minus and the projection becomes m minus one. The operators move one rung without changing total angular momentum.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.44,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "QUESTION",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Why not keep raising forever? A fixed vector magnitude cannot support an arbitrarily large z projection. Algebra says the same thing more sharply: the squared norm of every raised or lowered state must remain nonnegative.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.53,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "NORM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The raised-state norm contains j times j plus one minus m times m plus one. The lowered-state norm contains j times j plus one minus m times m minus one. Neither expression may be negative.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "calculate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.06,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "TOP",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "At the top rung, raising must give zero. Setting that norm factor to zero makes the maximum projection m equal j. The ladder stops because there is no normalizable state above it.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "collapse"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.05,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "BOTTOM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "At the bottom rung, lowering must give zero. The minimum projection is minus j. So the allowed values run from minus j to plus j in unit steps, for a total of two j plus one states.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "collapse"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.58,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "QUANTIZATION",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Because the number of unit steps from minus j to plus j is two j, that number must be an integer. Ladder algebra therefore allows j equal zero, one half, one, three halves, and so on.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.48,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "act": "ORBITAL SCOPE",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "For orbital angular momentum, we rename j as ell. Single-valued spatial wavefunctions restrict ell to nonnegative integers. Half-integer values belong to spin or other intrinsic angular momentum, not ordinary orbital spherical harmonics.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 15.3,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "act": "MAGNITUDE",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Once j is fixed, total magnitude is h-bar times the square root of j times j plus one. The projection ladder changes m, not that magnitude. Every rung is a different orientation state inside one multiplet.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.5,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "act": "EXAMPLE",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Take orbital ell equals two. The allowed projections are minus two, minus one, zero, one, and two h-bar: five rungs. The magnitude is h-bar root six, larger than the maximum projection two h-bar.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.69,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "act": "CAVEAT",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "The ladder picture does not mean a hidden classical arrow jumps between literal tilts. It organizes eigenstates and measurement outcomes. Superpositions can combine rungs, while a projection measurement returns one allowed m value.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.29,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B12.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "act": "YOUR TURN",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Your turn. For j equals three halves, list the rungs. They are minus three halves, minus one half, plus one half, and plus three halves. Four states, matching two j plus one.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "calculate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B13.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.05,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B13.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B14",
      "act": "RECAP",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Why does angular momentum come in a ladder? Raising and lowering shift projection by one, nonnegative norms force a top and bottom, and the endpoints quantize j and m. Orbital boundary conditions then restrict ell to integers.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B14.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.46,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B14.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:03:42"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B15",
      "act": "OUTRO",
      "estimated_duration_s": 5,
      "narration_text": "Why Angular Momentum Comes in a Ladder. Liam, in for Bear.",
